    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Vegetarians for Labels</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>David Koch letter suggests US food makers follow British example and label foods as vegetarian (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re: ''Mainstream Organics: Britain Stocks Up,'' June 21. In addition to national organic standards (and not ones defined by agribusiness giants), a British practice we Americans could happily adopt is the labeling of vegetarian foods. Most food products in Britain carry a stylish green ''V'' on their labels, indicating at a glance that a potential purchase is free from animal products like fats, gelatin and, almost impossible to know in this country, rennet, which is often found in cheese. A ''V'' is a  marketing bonus, not a red letter, a plus many consumers would appreciate.</p>
        <p>DAVID KOCH  New York</p>
      </block>
